# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electromagnetic-compatibility
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] In electrical engineering, a **common-mode signal** is the identical component of voltage present at both input terminals of an electrical device.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] In telecommunication, the common-mode signal on a transmission line is also known as **longitudinal voltage**.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] In most electrical circuits, desired signals are transferred by a differential voltage between two conductors.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] When referenced to the local common or ground, a common-mode signal appears on both lines of a two-wire cable, in phase and with equal amplitudes.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Technically, a common-mode voltage is one-half the vector sum of the voltages from each conductor of a balanced circuit to local ground or common.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Noise induced into a cable, or transmitted from a cable, usually occurs in the common mode, as the same signal tends to be picked up by both conductors in a two-wire cable.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Likewise, RF noise transmitted from a cable tends to emanate from both conductors.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Elimination of common-mode signals on cables entering or leaving electronic equipment is important to ensure electromagnetic compatibility.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Unless the intention is to transmit or receive radio signals, an electronic designer generally designs electronic circuits to minimise or eliminate common-mode effects.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/common-mode-signal] Common-mode rejection ratio is a measure of how well a circuit eliminates common-mode interference.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In electronics, **crosstalk** (**XT**) is a phenomenon by which a signal transmitted on one circuit or channel of a transmission system creates an undesired effect in another circuit or channel.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Crosstalk is usually caused by undesired capacitive, inductive, or conductive coupling from one circuit or channel to another.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Where the electric, magnetic, or traveling fields of two electric signals overlap, the electromagnetic interference created causes crosstalk.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] For example, crosstalk can comprise magnetic fields that induce a smaller signal in neighboring wires.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In electrical circuits sharing a common signal return path, electrical impedance in the return path creates **common impedance coupling** between the signals, resulting in crosstalk.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Crosstalk is a significant issue in structured cabling, audio electronics, integrated circuit design, wireless communication and other communications systems.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In structured cabling, crosstalk refers to electromagnetic interference from one unshielded twisted pair to another twisted pair, normally running in parallel.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Signals traveling through adjacent pairs of wire create magnetic fields that interact with each other, inducing interference in the neighboring pair.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] The pair causing the interference is called the *disturbing pair*, while the pair experiencing the interference is the *disturbed pair*.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] NEXT is a measure of the ability of a cable to reject crosstalk, so the higher the NEXT value, the greater the rejection of crosstalk at the local connection.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] because the interference between the two signals in the cable is measured at the same end of the cable as the interfering transmitter.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] The NEXT value for a given cable type is generally expressed in decibels per feet or decibels per 1000 feet and varies with the frequency of transmission.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] General specifications for cabling (such as CAT 5) usually include the minimum NEXT values.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] PSNEXT is a NEXT measurement which includes the sum of crosstalk contributions from all adjacent pairs as an algebraic sum of the NEXT of the three wire pairs as they affect the fourth pair in a four-pair cable (e.g., Category 6 cable).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] states that the testing process for PSNEXT consists of measuring all pair-to-pair crosstalk combinations and then summing all of the values for each pair.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] The specification was developed to directly address the effect of transmissions on multiple adjacent pairs on the pair being tested and is relevant to all connecting hardware and associated communications cables.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] uses all four wire pairs simultaneously and bidirectionally.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] The additional wire pair usage and growing bandwidth increases the need to keep NEXT in check.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] FEXT measures the interference between two pairs of a cable measured at the far end of the cable with respect to the interfering transmitter.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] ELFEXT measures the FEXT with attenuation compensation.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] AXT is interference caused by other cables routed close to the cable of interest as opposed to signals contained in the same cable.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In stereo audio reproduction, crosstalk can refer to signal leakage across from one program channel to another, reducing channel separation and stereo imaging.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Crosstalk between channels in mixing consoles, and between studio feeds is a much more noticeable problem, as these are likely to be carrying very different programs or material.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Crosstalk is an electrical effect and can be quantified with a crosstalk measurement.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Crosstalk measurements are made on audio systems to determine the amount of signal leaking from one channel to another.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] The Independent Broadcasting Authority published a weighting curve for use in crosstalk measurement that gives due emphasis to the subjective audibility of different frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In the absence of any international standards, this is still in use despite the demise of the IBA.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Good crosstalk performance for a stereo system is not difficult to achieve in today's digital audio systems, though it is difficult to keep below the desired figure of −30 dB or so on vinyl recordings and FM radio.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In telecommunication or telephony, crosstalk is often distinguishable as pieces of speech or in-band signaling tones leaking from other people's connections.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] If the connection is analog, twisted pair cabling can often be used to reduce crosstalk.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Alternatively, the signals can be converted to digital form, which is typically less susceptible to crosstalk.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In wireless communication, crosstalk is often denoted co-channel interference, and is related to adjacent-channel interference.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In integrated circuit design, crosstalk normally refers to a signal affecting another nearby signal.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] Usually, the coupling is capacitive, and to the nearest neighbor, but other forms of coupling and effects on signal further away are sometimes important, especially in analog designs.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] See signal integrity for tools used to measure and prevent this problem, and substrate coupling for a discussion of crosstalk conveyed through the integrated circuit substrate.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] There are a wide variety of repair solutions, with increased spacing, wire re-ordering, and shielding being the most common.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In full-field optical coherence tomography, "crosstalk" refers to the phenomenon that due to highly scattering objects, multiple scattered photons reach the image plane and generate a coherent signal after travelling a path length that matches that of the sample depth within a coherence length.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/crosstalk] In stereoscopic 3D displays, crosstalk refers to the incomplete isolation of the left and right image channels so that one bleeds into the other – like a double exposure, which produces a ghosting effect.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC pursues three main classes of issue.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Emission* is the generation of electromagnetic energy, whether deliberate or accidental, by some source and its release into the environment.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC studies the unwanted emissions and the countermeasures which may be taken in order to reduce unwanted emissions.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The second class, *susceptibility*, is the tendency of electrical equipment, referred to as the victim, to malfunction or break down in the presence of unwanted emissions, which are known as radio-frequency interference (RFI).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Immunity* is the opposite of susceptibility, being the ability of equipment to function correctly in the presence of RFI, with the discipline of "hardening" equipment being known equally as susceptibility or immunity.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] A third class studied is *coupling*, which is the mechanism by which emitted interference reaches the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Interference mitigation and hence electromagnetic compatibility may be achieved by addressing any or all of these issues, i.e., quieting the sources of interference, inhibiting coupling paths and/or hardening the potential victims.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In practice, many of the engineering techniques used, such as grounding and shielding, apply to all three issues.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The earliest EMC issue was lightning strike (lightning electromagnetic pulse, or LEMP) on ships and buildings.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Lightning rods or lightning conductors began to appear in the mid-18th century.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] With the advent of widespread electricity generation and power supply lines from the late 19th century on, problems also arose with equipment short-circuit failure affecting the power supply, and with local fire and shock hazard when the power line was struck by lightning.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Power stations were provided with output circuit breakers.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Buildings and appliances would soon be provided with input fuses, and later in the 20th century miniature circuit breakers (MCB) would come into use.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] It may be said that radio interference and its correction arose with the first spark-gap experiment of Marconi in the late 1800s.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] As radio communications developed in the first half of the 20th century, interference between broadcast radio signals began to occur and an international regulatory framework was set up to ensure interference-free communications.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Switching devices became commonplace through the middle of the 20th century, typically in petrol powered cars and motorcycles but also in domestic appliances such as thermostats and refrigerators.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This caused transient interference with domestic radio and (after World War II) TV reception, and in due course laws were passed requiring the suppression of such interference sources.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge (ESD) problems first arose with accidental electric spark discharges in hazardous environments such as coal mines and when refuelling aircraft or motor cars.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Safe working practices had to be developed.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] After World War II the military became increasingly concerned with the effects of nuclear electromagnetic pulse (NEMP), lightning strike, and even high-powered radar beams, on vehicle and mobile equipment of all kinds, and especially aircraft electrical systems.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] When high RF emission levels from other sources became a potential problem (such as with the advent of microwave ovens), certain frequency bands were designated for Industrial, Scientific and Medical (ISM) use, allowing emission levels limited only by thermal safety standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Later, the International Telecommunication Union adopted a Recommendation providing limits of radiation from ISM devices in order to protect radiocommunications.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] A variety of issues such as sideband and harmonic emissions, broadband sources, and the ever-increasing popularity of electrical switching devices and their victims, resulted in a steady development of standards and laws.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the late 1970s, the popularity of modern digital circuitry rapidly grew.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] As the technology developed, with ever-faster switching speeds (increasing emissions) and lower circuit voltages (increasing susceptibility), EMC increasingly became a source of concern.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Many more nations became aware of EMC as a growing problem and issued directives to the manufacturers of digital electronic equipment, which set out the essential manufacturer requirements before their equipment could be marketed or sold.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Organizations in individual nations, across Europe and worldwide, were set up to maintain these directives and associated standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1979, the American FCC published a regulation that required the electromagnetic emissions of all "digital devices" to be below certain limits.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This regulatory environment led to a sharp growth in the EMC industry supplying specialist devices and equipment, analysis and design software, and testing and certification services.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Low-voltage digital circuits, especially CMOS transistors, became more susceptible to ESD damage as they were miniaturised and, despite the development of on-chip hardening techniques, a new ESD regulatory regime had to be developed.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the 1980s on the explosive growth in mobile communications and broadcast media channels put huge pressure on the available airspace.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Regulatory authorities began squeezing band allocations closer and closer together, relying on increasingly sophisticated EMC control methods, especially in the digital communications domain, to keep cross-channel interference to acceptable levels.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Digital systems are inherently less susceptible than analogue systems, and also offer far easier ways (such as software) to implement highly sophisticated protection and error-correction measures.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1985, the USA released the ISM bands for low-power mobile digital communications, leading to the development of Wi-Fi and remotely-operated car door keys.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This approach relies on the intermittent nature of ISM interference and use of sophisticated error-correction methods to ensure lossless reception during the quiet gaps between any bursts of interference.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC ensures the correct operation, in the same electromagnetic environment, of different equipment items which use or respond to electromagnetic phenomena, and the avoidance of any interference.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Another way of saying this is that EMC is the control of EMI so that unwanted effects are prevented.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Besides understanding the phenomena in themselves, EMC also addresses the countermeasures, such as control regimes, design and measurement, which should be taken in order to prevent emissions from causing any adverse effect.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC is often understood as the control of electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electromagnetic interference divides into several categories according to the source and signal characteristics.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be man-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference comprises a given range of frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This type is naturally divided into sub-categories according to frequency range, and as a whole is sometimes referred to as "DC to daylight".
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] One common classification is into narrowband and broadband, according to the spread of the frequency range.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, is a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pulse signals divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] When a source emits interference, it follows a route to the victim known as the coupling path.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] There are four basic coupling mechanisms: conductive, capacitive, magnetic or inductive, and radiative.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Any coupling path can be broken down into one or more of these coupling mechanisms working together.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Source and victim act as radio antennas: the source emits or radiates an electromagnetic wave which propagates across the space in between and is picked up or received by the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The damaging effects of electromagnetic interference pose unacceptable risks in many areas of technology, and it is necessary to control such interference and reduce the risks to acceptable levels.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The risk posed by the threat is usually statistical in nature, so much of the work in threat characterisation and standards setting is based on reducing the probability of disruptive EMI to an acceptable level, rather than its assured elimination.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] For a complex or novel piece of equipment, this may require the production of a dedicated *EMC control plan* summarizing the application of the above and specifying additional documents required.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Breaking a coupling path is equally effective at either the start or the end of the path, therefore many aspects of good EMC design practice apply equally to potential sources and to potential victims.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] A design which easily couples energy to the outside world will equally easily couple energy in and will be susceptible.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] A single improvement will often reduce both emissions and susceptibility.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Grounding and shielding aim to reduce emissions or divert EMI away from the victim by providing an alternative, low-impedance path.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Testing is required to confirm that a particular device meets the required standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] It is divided broadly into emissions testing and susceptibility testing.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Open-area test sites, or OATS, are the reference sites in most standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] They are especially useful for emissions testing of large equipment systems.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] However, RF testing of a physical prototype is most often carried out indoors, in a specialized EMC test chamber.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Types of the chamber include anechoic, reverberation and the gigahertz transverse electromagnetic cell (GTEM cell).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Sometimes computational electromagnetics simulations are used to test virtual models.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Like all compliance testing, it is important that the test equipment, including the test chamber or site and any software used, be properly calibrated and maintained.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typically, a given run of tests for a particular piece of equipment will require an *EMC test plan* and a follow-up *test report*.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The full test program may require the production of several such documents.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Emissions are typically measured for radiated field strength and where appropriate for conducted emissions along cables and wiring.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive (magnetic) and capacitive (electric) field strengths are near-field effects and are only important if the device under test (DUT) is designed for a location close to other electrical equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] For conducted emissions, typical transducers include the LISN (line impedance stabilization network) or AMN (artificial mains network) and the RF current clamp.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] For radiated emission measurement, antennas are used as transducers.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typical antennas specified include dipole, biconical, log-periodic, double ridged guide and conical log-spiral designs.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated emissions must be measured in all directions around the DUT.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Specialized EMI test receivers or EMI analyzers are used for EMC compliance testing.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] These incorporate bandwidths and detectors as specified by international EMC standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] An EMI receiver may be based on a spectrum analyser to measure the emission levels of the DUT across a wide band of frequencies (frequency domain), or on a tunable narrower-band device which is swept through the desired frequency range.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMI receivers along with specified transducers can often be used for both conducted and radiated emissions.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pre-selector filters may also be used to reduce the effect of strong out-of-band signals on the front-end of the receiver.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some pulse emissions are more usefully characterized using an oscilloscope to capture the pulse waveform in the time domain.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated field susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered source of RF or EM energy and a radiating antenna to direct the energy at the potential victim or device under test (DUT).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conducted voltage and current susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered signal generator, and a current clamp or other type of transformer to inject the test signal.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Transient or EMP signals are used to test the immunity of the DUT against powerline disturbances including surges, lightning strikes and switching noise.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In motor vehicles, similar tests are performed on battery and signal lines.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The transient pulse may be generated digitally and passed through a broadband pulse amplifier, or applied directly to the transducer from a specialized pulse generator.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge testing is typically performed with a piezo spark generator called an "ESD pistol".
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Higher energy pulses, such as lightning or nuclear EMP simulations, can require a large current clamp or a large antenna which completely surrounds the DUT.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some antennas are so large that they are located outdoors, and care must be taken not to cause an EMP hazard to the surrounding environment.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Several organizations, both national and international, work to promote international co-operation on standardization (harmonization), including publishing various EMC standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Where possible, a standard developed by one organization may be adopted with little or no change by others.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] This helps for example to harmonize national standards across Europe.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with national or international standards is usually laid down by laws passed by individual nations.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Different nations can require compliance with different standards.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In European law, EU directive 2014/30/EU (previously 2004/108/EC) on EMC defines the rules for the placing on the market/putting into service of electric/electronic equipment within the European Union.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] The Directive applies to a vast range of equipment including electrical and electronic appliances, systems and installations.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Manufacturers of electric and electronic devices are advised to run EMC tests in order to comply with compulsory CE-labeling.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] More are given in the list of EMC directives.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with the applicable harmonised standards whose reference is listed in the OJEU under the EMC Directive gives presumption of conformity with the corresponding essential requirements of the EMC Directive.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 2019, the USA adopted a program for the protection of critical infrastructure against an electromagnetic pulse, whether caused by a geomagnetic storm or a high-altitude nuclear weapon.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Both human-made and natural sources generate changing electrical currents and voltages that can cause EMI: ignition systems, cellular network of mobile phones, lightning, solar flares, and auroras (northern/southern lights).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] It can also affect mobile phones, FM radios, and televisions, as well as observations for radio astronomy and atmospheric science.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] EMI can be used intentionally for radio jamming, as in electronic warfare.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Since the earliest days of radio communications, the negative effects of interference from both intentional and unintentional transmissions have been felt and the need to manage the radio frequency spectrum became apparent.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In 1933, a meeting of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in Paris recommended the International Special Committee on Radio Interference (CISPR) be set up to deal with the emerging problem of EMI.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] CISPR subsequently produced technical publications covering measurement and test techniques and recommended emission and immunity limits.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These have evolved over the decades and form the basis of much of the world's EMC regulations today.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In 1979, legal limits were imposed on electromagnetic emissions from all digital equipment by the FCC in the US in response to the increased number of digital systems that were interfering with wired and radio communications.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Test methods and limits were based on CISPR publications, although similar limits were already enforced in parts of Europe.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In the mid 1980s, the European Union member states adopted a number of "new approach" directives with the intention of standardizing technical requirements for products so that they do not become a barrier to trade within the EC.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] One of these was the EMC Directive (89/336/EC) and it applies to all equipment placed on the market or taken into service.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Its scope covers all apparatus "liable to cause electromagnetic disturbance or the performance of which is liable to be affected by such disturbance".
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This was the first time there was a legal requirement on immunity, as well as emissions on apparatus intended for the general population.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Although there may be additional costs involved for some products to give them a known level of immunity, it increases their perceived quality as they are able to co-exist with apparatus in the active EM environment of modern times and with fewer problems.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Many countries now have similar requirements for products to meet some level of electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) regulation.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be human-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference arises where the source continuously emits at a given range of frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, arises where the source emits a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Sources divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted electromagnetic interference is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI, which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic disturbances in the EM field of a conductor will no longer be confined to the surface of the conductor and will radiate away from it.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This persists in all conductors and mutual inductance between two radiated electromagnetic fields will result in EMI.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the technical terms which are employed can be used with differing meanings.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Some phenomena may be referred to by various different terms.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These terms are used here in a widely accepted way, which is consistent with other articles in the encyclopedia.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The basic arrangement of noise emitter or source, coupling path and victim, receptor or sink is shown in the figure below.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Source and victim are usually electronic hardware devices, though the source may be a natural phenomenon such as a lightning strike, electrostatic discharge (ESD) or, in one famous case, the Big Bang at the origin of the Universe.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] For example the lower path in the diagram involves inductive, conductive and capacitive modes.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body, for example a transmission line, wire, cable, PCB trace or metal enclosure.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling occurs where the source and victim are separated by a short distance (typically less than a wavelength).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Strictly, "Inductive coupling" can be of two kinds, electrical induction and magnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] It is common to refer to electrical induction as *capacitive coupling*, and to magnetic induction as *inductive coupling*.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance, typically more than a wavelength.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This is also a definition used by the frequency administration to provide frequency assignments and assignment of frequency channels to radio stations or systems, as well as to analyze electromagnetic compatibility between radiocommunication services.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted EMI is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] For lower frequencies, EMI is caused by conduction and, for higher frequencies, by radiation.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] EMI through the ground wire is also very common in an electrical facility.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Interference tends to be more troublesome with older radio technologies such as analogue amplitude modulation, which have no way of distinguishing unwanted in-band signals from the intended signal, and the omnidirectional antennas used with broadcast systems.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Newer radio systems incorporate several improvements that enhance the selectivity.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In digital radio systems, such as Wi-Fi, error-correction techniques can be used.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Spread-spectrum and frequency-hopping techniques can be used with both analogue and digital signalling to improve resistance to interference.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] A highly directional receiver, such as a parabolic antenna or a diversity receiver, can be used to select one signal in space to the exclusion of others.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The most extreme example of digital spread-spectrum signalling to date is ultra-wideband (UWB), which proposes the use of large sections of the radio spectrum at low amplitudes to transmit high-bandwidth digital data.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In the United States, the 1982 Public Law 97-259 allowed the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to regulate the susceptibility of consumer electronic equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Potential sources of RFI and EMI include: various types of transmitters, doorbell transformers, toaster ovens, electric blankets, ultrasonic pest control devices, electric bug zappers, heating pads, and touch controlled lamps.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Multiple CRT computer monitors or televisions sitting too close to one another can sometimes cause a "shimmy" effect in each other, due to the electromagnetic nature of their picture tubes, especially when one of their de-gaussing coils is activated.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic interference at 2.4 GHz may be caused by 802.11b, 802.11g and 802.11n wireless devices, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors and cordless telephones, video senders, and microwave ovens.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Switching loads (inductive, capacitive, and resistive), such as electric motors, transformers, heaters, lamps, ballast, power supplies, etc., all cause electromagnetic interference especially at currents above 2 A.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The usual method used for suppressing EMI is by connecting a snubber network, a resistor in series with a capacitor, across a pair of contacts.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] While this may offer modest EMI reduction at very low currents, snubbers do not work at currents over 2 A with electromechanical contacts.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Another method for suppressing EMI is the use of ferrite core noise suppressors (or ferrite beads), which are inexpensive and which clip on to the power lead of the offending device or the compromised device.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Switched-mode power supplies can be a source of EMI, but have become less of a problem as design techniques have improved, such as integrated power factor correction.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Most countries have legal requirements that mandate electromagnetic compatibility: electronic and electrical hardware must still work correctly when subjected to certain amounts of EMI, and should not emit EMI, which could interfere with other equipment (such as radios).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Radio frequency signal quality has declined throughout the 21st century by roughly one decibel per year as the spectrum becomes increasingly crowded.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This has inflicted a Red Queen's race on the mobile phone industry as companies have been forced to put up more cellular towers (at new frequencies) that then cause more interference thereby requiring more investment by the providers and frequent upgrades of mobile phones to match.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These are civilian standards for domestic, commercial, industrial and automotive sectors.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These standards form the basis of other national or regional standards, most notably the European Norms (EN) written by CENELEC (European committee for electrotechnical standardisation).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] US organizations include the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the American National Standards Institute (ANSI), and the US Military (MILSTD).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Integrated circuits are often a source of EMI, but they must usually couple their energy to larger objects such as heatsinks, circuit board planes and cables to radiate significantly.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] On integrated circuits, important means of reducing EMI are: the use of bypass or decoupling capacitors on each active device (connected across the power supply, as close to the device as possible), rise time control of high-speed signals using series resistors, and IC power supply pin filtering.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Shielding is usually a last resort after other techniques have failed, because of the added expense of shielding components such as conductive gaskets.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] At lower frequencies, such as 133 MHz, radiation is almost exclusively via I/O cables; RF noise gets onto the power planes and is coupled to the line drivers via the VCC and GND pins.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The RF is then coupled to the cable through the line driver as common-mode noise.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Since the noise is common-mode, shielding has very little effect, even with differential pairs.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The RF energy is capacitively coupled from the signal pair to the shield and the shield itself does the radiating.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] One cure for this is to use a braid-breaker or choke to reduce the common-mode signal.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] At higher frequencies, usually above 500 MHz, traces get electrically longer and higher above the plane.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Two techniques are used at these frequencies: wave shaping with series resistors and embedding the traces between the two planes.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] If all these measures still leave too much EMI, shielding such as RF gaskets and copper or conductive tape can be used.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Most digital equipment is designed with metal or conductive-coated plastic cases.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Any unshielded semiconductor (e.g. an integrated circuit) will tend to act as a detector for those radio signals commonly found in the domestic environment (e.g. mobile phones).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Such a detector can demodulate the high frequency mobile phone carrier (e.g., GSM850 and GSM1900, GSM900 and GSM1800) and produce low-frequency (e.g., 217 Hz) demodulated signals.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This demodulation manifests itself as unwanted audible buzz in audio appliances such as microphone amplifier, speaker amplifier, car radio, telephones etc.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Adding onboard EMI filters or special layout techniques can help in bypassing EMI or improving RF immunity.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Some ICs are designed (e.g., LMV831-LMV834, MAX9724) to have integrated RF filters or a special design that helps reduce any demodulation of high-frequency carrier.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Designers often need to carry out special tests for RF immunity of parts to be used in a system.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These tests are often done in an anechoic chamber with a controlled RF environment where the test vectors produce a RF field similar to that produced in an actual environment.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Interference in radio astronomy, where it is commonly referred to as radio-frequency interference (RFI), is any source of transmission that is within the observed frequency band other than the celestial sources themselves.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Because transmitters on and around the Earth can be many times stronger than the astronomical signal of interest, RFI is a major concern for performing radio astronomy.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the frequency bands that are very important for radio astronomy, such as the 21-cm HI line at 1420 MHz, are protected by regulation.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] However, modern radio-astronomical observatories such as VLA, LOFAR, and ALMA have a very large bandwidth over which they can observe.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Techniques to deal with RFI range from filters in hardware to advanced algorithms in software.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] One way to deal with strong transmitters is to filter out the frequency of the source completely.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This is for example the case for the LOFAR observatory, which filters out the FM radio stations between 90 and 110 MHz.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] It is important to remove such strong sources of interference as soon as possible, because they might "saturate" the highly sensitive receivers (amplifiers and analogue-to-digital converters), which means that the received signal is stronger than the receiver can handle.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] However, filtering out a frequency band implies that these frequencies can never be observed with the instrument.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] A common technique to deal with RFI within the observed frequency bandwidth, is to employ RFI detection in software.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Such software can find samples in time, frequency or time-frequency space that are contaminated by an interfering source.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These samples are subsequently ignored in further analysis of the observed data.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] This process is often referred to as *data flagging*.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Because most transmitters have a small bandwidth and are not continuously present such as lightning or citizens' band (CB) radio devices, most of the data remains available for the astronomical analysis.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] However, data flagging can not solve issues with continuous broad-band transmitters, such as windmills, digital video or digital audio transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Another way to manage RFI is to establish a radio quiet zone (RQZ).
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] RQZ is a well-defined area surrounding receivers that has special regulations to reduce RFI in favor of radio astronomy observations within the zone.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The regulations may include special management of spectrum and power flux or power flux-density limitations.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The controls within the zone may cover elements other than radio transmitters or radio devices.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These include aircraft controls and control of unintentional radiators such as industrial, scientific and medical devices, vehicles, and power lines.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The first RQZ for radio astronomy is United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), established in 1958.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Prior to the introduction of Wi-Fi, one of the biggest applications of 5 GHz band was the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The decision to use 5 GHz spectrum for Wi-Fi was finalized at the World Radiocommunication Conference in 2003; however, meteorological authorities were not involved in the process.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] The subsequent lax implementation and misconfiguration of DFS had caused significant disruption in weather radar operations in a number of countries around the world.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] In Hungary, the weather radar system was declared non-operational for more than a month.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Due to the severity of interference, South African weather services ended up abandoning C band operation, switching their radar network to S band.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Transmissions on adjacent bands to those used by passive remote sensing, such as weather satellites, have caused interference, sometimes significant.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] There is concern that adoption of insufficiently regulated 5G could produce major interference issues.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] Significant interference can impair numerical weather prediction performance and incur negative economic and public safety impacts.
[src:electromagnetic-compatibility/electromagnetic-interference] These concerns led US Secretary of Commerce Wilbur Ross and NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine in February 2019 to urge the FCC to cancel a proposed spectrum auction, which was rejected.
